summary:
Sooo is nobody gonna talk about the reference in this scene?
So this is the last scene with Aziraphale and Crowley. They're...
body:
Sooo is nobody gonna talk about the reference in this scene?

So this is the last scene with Aziraphale and Crowley. They’re dining at the Ritz, when the narrator mentions that “a nightingale sang in Berkeley Square”.

That is in reference of the 1939 song “A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square”

That’s all nice and well but

BUT

BUT

It’s a love song.

I mean look at this:

I’m not saying that basically makes the ship canon buuuuuuuut

summary: I resonate to Aziraphale. I get Aziraphale. Because it’s just like-- When he’s around humans, he’s on his very best behaviour....
body:
I resonate to Aziraphale. I get Aziraphale.

Because it’s just like–

When he’s around humans, he’s on his very best behaviour. He’s kind and gentle and fixes their bikes and tells them to have nice dreams and inspires them and soothes them and, and, and, gosh, isn’t he nice, really, he’s just such an angel–

And when he’s by himself he introverts as hard as possible–

And when he’s with Crowley, the one being who gets it, he just - well, after a drink or two, plausible deniability don’t you know - he just yodels:

“I had the most ghastly day, I had to smile at everyone and there were three miracles and they were all soppy nonsense, and can you imagine there were customers in my shop? actually? in? my? shop? and they wouldn’t leave and then the telephone rang twice and the questions were so stupid and then I had to go out last minute and solve someone’s crisis of faith and I just, Crowley, I’m exhausted, really, how do you suppose all the others do it? Am I being a bit over the top? You can tell me, really, be honest.”

Crowley is, with some effort, not smiling.

“Maybe you should try being a demon. Really properly being one, I mean. I think we have more fun. I know I do.”

“Oh, it’s all awful, I’m just exhausted, don’t even bother tempting me, I’m sure it would be exactly the same; pour me another, there’s a kind soul, and let’s watch the television broadcast about the ‘alien’ with the box and the scientific devices and I don’t want to say another word.”

My baby~~~

body:
Crowley’s “I was an attractive child, I could juggle. I was worth five pigs at least” really got me thinking

Like

I can’t juggle, but I have a few other useless skills that could contribute to my pig worth.

Am I worth three? Fifteen? We may never know.

I can’t juggle, but I have a few other useless skills that could contribute to my pig worth.

Am I worth three? Fifteen? We may never know.

summary:
"I'm looking for a book about the Shambles," the young woman said.
 
"The Shambles?" I was unfamiliar with the name, so I took...
caption:
“I’m looking for a book about the Shambles,” the young woman said.

“The Shambles?” I was unfamiliar with the name, so I took a wild guess. “Are they musicians?”

She looked confused. “Musicians?”

Crowley, standing nearby, decided to be helpful. “A band. Like the Beatles. Or the Rutles. Or Duran Duran.”

She shook her head. “No, the Shambles isn’t a band. It’s a place. A Chicago neighborhood. In fact, I think it’s this neighborhood. Is this the Shambles?”

Always ready to insult my shop, Crowley replied. “Well, it’s a shambles.”

The woman shook her head again. “There’s a neighborhood called the Shambles, but I’m not sure of the exact boundaries. It’s hard to find. But on my way here, I crossed Old Street, and went past Saunders Park. I’m pretty sure that’s in the Shambles. There’s a guidebook about it. I can’t remember the exact title. It’s something like An Ambling Tour of the Shambles. I think there were two authors. Maybe Gene? Neil?”

“Eugene O'Neill?” I asked.

“I’m sorry, I can’t quite think of the names,” she said. “One of the last names was something like ‘Grayman,’ but I don’t think that’s it.”

“Grayman…” Crowley thought for a moment. “Grayson, perhaps? Dick Grayson and Eugene O'Neill?” Crowley asked.

“No,” she answered. “But they were short names, like four letters.”

“Dick Grayson and Shit O'Neill?”

Her irritation began to show. “No! One was definitely Gene something. And I feel like one of the names was an animal name.”

“Ah,” Crowley said. “Now we’re getting somewhere. Gene Simmons and Cat Stevens! Who better to write a book about Duran Duran?”

“It’s got nothing to do with Duran Duran! And I told you, the Shambles isn’t a band.”

“People said the same thing about Duran Duran.”

I decided to speak up, realizing that the poor woman had reached the limits of her patience. “Don’t mind my friend,” I said. “So, you said there were two authors: One was possibly named Neil, another might have been named Gene. One last name sounded similar to Grayman, and one might have been the name of an animal.”

Crowley turned toward me. “Caiman!” he exclaimed. “That sounds similar to Grayman, and it’s an animal. Do you have any books by Neil Armstrong and Gene Caiman?”

The woman shook her head in frustration and stormed out.

It was only later that I stumbled across this little book. Perhaps it was the one she wanted.
